To implement a Java program that connects to a Cassandra database, you will need the DataStax Java Driver for Apache Cassandra. You can add it as a dependency in your project using Maven or Gradle.

For Maven, add this to your `pom.xml`:

```xml
<dependencies>
  <dependency>
    <groupId>com.datastax.oss</groupId>
    <artifactId>java-driver-core</artifactId>
    <version>4.11.1</version>
  </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

For Gradle, add this to your `build.gradle`:

```groovy
dependencies {
  implementation 'com.datastax.oss:java-driver-core:4.11.1'
}
```

Here's an example of a Java program that connects to a Cassandra database, creates a keyspace and table, inserts sample data, and runs a CQL query to retrieve specific records based on given criteria:

```java
import com.datastax.oss.driver.api.core.CqlSession;
import com.datastax.oss.driver.api.core.cql.ResultSet;
import com.datastax.oss.driver.api.core.cql.Row;

public class CassandraExample {

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    // Connect to the Cassandra cluster
    try (CqlSession session = CqlSession.builder().withKeyspace("test_keyspace").build()) {
      // Create a new keyspace
      session.execute(
          "CREATE KEYSPACE IF NOT EXISTS test_keyspace WITH replication "
              + "= {'class':'SimpleStrategy', 'replication_factor':1};");

      // Use the created keyspace
      session.execute("USE test_keyspace;");

      // Create a new table
      session.execute(
          "CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS users ("
              + "id UUID PRIMARY KEY,"
              + "name text,"
              + "age int);");

      // Insert sample data
      session.execute(
          "INSERT INTO users (id, name, age) VALUES (uuid(), 'Alice', 30);");
      session.execute(
          "INSERT INTO users (id, name, age) VALUES (uuid(), 'Bob', 25);");
      session.execute(
          "INSERT INTO users (id, name, age) VALUES (uuid(), 'Charlie', 35);");

      // Run a CQL query to retrieve specific records based on given criteria
      ResultSet resultSet = session.execute("SELECT * FROM users WHERE age >= 30;");

      // Output the retrieved records to the console
      System.out.println("Users with age >= 30:");
      for (Row row : resultSet) {
        System.out.printf("%s (%d years old)\n", row.getString("name"), row.getInt("age"));
      }
    }
  }
}
```

This program connects to a local Cassandra cluster, creates a keyspace called `test_keyspace`, and a table called `users`. It then inserts three sample records into the `users` table and runs a CQL query to retrieve all users with an age of 30 or older. Finally, it outputs the retrieved records to the console.

Make sure you have a running Cassandra instance before executing this code.

