draw((0,0)--D,Arrow(6));
draw((0,0)--V,red,Arrow(6));
draw((0,0)--R,blue,Arrow(6));
draw(V--R,dashed);

label("$\mathbf{v}$", V, NE);
label("$\mathbf{r}$", R, SE);
[/asy]

Then the reflection of $\mathbf{r}$ is $\mathbf{v},$ so $\mathbf{R} \mathbf{r} = \mathbf{v}.$  Thus,
\[\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{R} \mathbf{r} = \mathbf{R}^2 \mathbf{v}.\]Since this holds for all vectors $\mathbf{v},$ $\mathbf{R}^2 = \mathbf{I} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}.$

